---
import Base from "@layouts/Base.astro";
import { BASE } from "@/lib/site";
import { loadDidCi } from "@/lib/data";

const ci = loadDidCi();
const fmt = (v: number) => `${v < 0 ? "−" : "+"}${Math.abs(v).toFixed(2)}`;

const claims = [
  { strength: "strong",   label: "NO₂ declined more over the congestion zone than over the rest of NYC, after adjusting for atmospheric drift." },
  { strength: "strong",   label: "The placebo year shows little comparable signal over Manhattan, supporting a policy interpretation." },
  { strength: "moderate", label: "Bridges and tunnels saw a small reduction in vehicle entries (~1.75 percentage points)." },
  { strength: "moderate", label: "Bus ridership increased substantially, though entangled with simultaneous service expansions." },
  { strength: "weak",     label: "Yellow-taxi spillover at the cordon edge does not appear in the data; rideshare data was unavailable." },
] as const;
---
<Base
  title="Verdict"
  description="A synthesis of what this analysis suggests, what remains uncertain, and where the analysis reaches its limits."
>
  <section class="wrap section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Chapter 04 · Verdict</p>
    <h1>What the evidence suggests, what remains uncertain, and where the analysis reaches its limits.</h1>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap section">
    <p class="eyebrow">The clearest finding</p>
    <h2>A measurable, modest, spatially coherent improvement.</h2>
    <p>
      The evidence suggests congestion pricing was associated with measurable
      improvements in air quality over Manhattan's congestion zone.
      Satellite-measured nitrogen dioxide declined more over Manhattan below
      60th Street than over the rest of the city, and the placebo comparison
      suggests this gap exceeds ordinary year-to-year atmospheric variation.
    </p>
    <p>
      After adjusting for background drift, the estimated zone-attributable
      improvement is approximately <strong>{fmt(ci.didOfDids.value)} percentage
      points</strong> [95% CI {fmt(ci.didOfDids.ci[0])} to {fmt(ci.didOfDids.ci[1])}].
      The signal is modest in magnitude but spatially coherent and
      methodologically robust.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Findings that proved smaller or conditional</p>
    <h2>Vehicle entries down, transit up unevenly, taxi spillover not detected.</h2>
    <p>
      The bridges difference-in-differences came in at <strong>−1.75 percentage
      points</strong> [95% CI: −3.32, −0.18] — a real but modest reduction in
      vehicle entries beyond ordinary fluctuation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bus ridership gained an estimated <strong>+10 percentage points</strong>
      above the placebo trajectory, but that result overlaps with the June
      2025 MTA service expansion in Queens and the addition of 16 enhanced
      routes citywide. Subway gained a cleaner <strong>+3.9 pp</strong>.
      Commuter-rail modes declined in both real and placebo windows,
      suggesting recovery saturation rather than a congestion-zone effect.
    </p>
    <p>
      The taxi-spillover hypothesis was tested across four predictions and
      did not appear consistently in yellow-taxi data. FHV records were
      unavailable at zone resolution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap section">
    <p class="eyebrow">What the analysis did not measure</p>
    <h2>Different instruments, different scales, different answers.</h2>
    <p>
      The Columbia and South Bronx Unite study, released as this analysis
      was being completed, reports PM2.5 increases at 17 of 19 ground
      monitors in the South Bronx during the congestion zone's first year,
      especially near major expressways. The satellite used here cannot
      resolve those neighborhood-block changes.
    </p>
    <p>
      FHV and Uber/Lyft trip records were unavailable at zone resolution.
      Indoor air, individual exposure, and longer-term trajectories are
      outside this dataset's scope. None of those gaps are evidence that the
      corresponding effects did not occur — they are evidence that this
      analysis cannot speak to them.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Confidence scorecard</p>
    <h2>Each claim, with the strength of evidence behind it.</h2>

    <ul class="scorecard">
      {claims.map((c) => (
        <li class:list={["score-item", `score-${c.strength}`]}>
          <span class="score-tag">{c.strength}</span>
          <span class="score-label">{c.label}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap section">
    <p class="eyebrow">A measured interpretation</p>
    <h2>Real, modest, uneven.</h2>
    <p>
      Congestion pricing appears to have produced a measurable, spatially
      coherent improvement in NYC's nitrogen dioxide pollution over the area
      where it operates. The improvement was modest in magnitude and
      unevenly distributed — most pronounced relative to higher-income, less
      transit-oriented neighborhoods, and smallest relative to lower-income,
      transit-dependent neighborhoods that experienced similar declines on
      their own.
    </p>
    <p>
      The findings do not support a story about congestion pricing
      transforming New York's air. They support a more specific story: a
      policy producing a detectable signal in one pollutant, over one zone,
      with effects that varied by neighborhood and that this analysis cannot
      fully decompose.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap section">
    <a class="next-card" href={`${BASE}/01-air/`}>
      <span class="next-eyebrow">Re-read · Chapter 01</span>
      <span class="next-title">The Air</span>
      <span class="next-tease">Back to the centerpiece finding.</span>
    </a>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .scorecard {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--s-4) auto 0;
    max-width: 880px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .score-item {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 120px 1fr;
    gap: var(--s-3);
    align-items: baseline;
    padding: var(--s-3) 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    text-align: left;
  }
  .score-tag {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--t-meta);
    letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    text-align: left;
  }
  .score-strong   .score-tag { color: var(--improve); }
  .score-moderate .score-tag { color: var(--ink); }
  .score-weak     .score-tag { color: var(--zone); }
  .score-label {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--t-body);
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--ink);
    text-align: left;
    max-width: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .score-item { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: var(--s-1); }
  }

  .next-card {
    display: block;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding: var(--s-4) 0;
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--ink);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    transition: background var(--d) var(--ease);
  }
  .next-card:hover { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--zone) 6%, transparent); }
  .next-eyebrow {
    display: block;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--t-meta);
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--zone);
    margin-bottom: var(--s-1);
  }
  .next-title {
    display: block;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.625rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-bottom: var(--s-1);
  }
  .next-tease {
    display: block;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    color: var(--ink-muted);
    max-width: 50ch;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
</style>
